			<part xml:id="Part-Truth">
				<title>Truth</title>
				
				<introduction>
					<p>
						Throughout scripture, Christians are exhorted in various ways and to various activities regarding <em>truth</em>.
						We are told that knowledge of "the truth" will "set [us] free"<fn>John 8:32</fn>, Christ calls Himself "the way, the truth, and the life"<fn>John 14:6</fn>, and says that his mission is to testify to the truth<fn>John 18:37; to which Pilate asks: "What is truth?"</fn>. Further, Paul exhorts believers to think on "whatever is true"<fn>Phil. 4:8</fn>.
						But what <em>is</em> truth? Can mathematics help us better apprehend and understand it?
					</p>
		
						<p>
							Mathematics is often thought of as one of the last bastions of objective truth.
							One widely accepted cultural norm is that if a statement is quantitative, or can be arrived at via a sequence of logical deductions, it is often considered "true", whereas statements that cannot be presented in such a way live in the realm of opinion. But what do mathematicians mean when they talk of a statement being "true"? The answer might surprise you.
						</p>
						
						<p>
							In this unit, we'll explore inductive and deductive reasoning, as well as formal logic. We'll explore the shortcomings of mathematical thinking in addition to its strengths.
						</p>
						
						<p>
							This chapter is heavily influenced by <em><url href="https://www.artofmathematics.org/books/truth-reasoning-certainty-and-proof">Discovering the Art of Mathematics: Truth, Reasoning, Certainty, and Proof</url></em> by Fleron, Hotchkiss, Ecke, and von Renesse.
						</p>
						
						<assemblage>
							<title>Learning Goals</title>
							<p>
								<statement>
									In this thematic unit, we will explore the following big ideas.
									<ul>
										<li>Inductive vs. deductive reasoning, truth vs. fact, and the strengths and weaknesses of each</li>
										<li>Axiomatic systems, logical connectives, and formal logic</li>
										<li>The search for complete and consistent logical foundations for mathematics in the late 19th/early 20th centuries</li>
										<li>Set theory and infinite cardinalities, including Russell's paradox and the continuum hypothesis</li>
										<li>The consequences of Godel's theorems</li>
									</ul>
								</statement>
							</p>
						</assemblage>
		
		
		
					</introduction>
			
			
			<chapter xml:id="Week-05">
				<title>Week 5: Feb. 8-12</title>
				
				<introduction>
					<p>
						This week, our focus is squarely on deductive reasoning.
						We'll explore axioms and consider what our own unproved assumptions are.
						We'll consider formal logic (that is, reasonign about compound statements whose truth values depend only on their structure and constituent elementary statements).
						We'll close the week with some time spent playing the social deduction game, <em>The Resistance</em>, and considering some deductive puzzles based on it.
					  </p>
					  <p>
					  	If you haven't passed your Cube checkpoint yet, make sure you're working on it! And please schedule a time to attempt it soon.
						  Also, the second reflection on M4HF is due next week, so start reading Chapters 6-7 now.
					  </p>
				</introduction>
				
				<section xml:id="Feb-08">
					<title>Feb. 8: Truth, Inductive Reasoning, and Reasoning from Axioms</title>
					
					
					<introduction>
						
						<p>
							Today we'll attempt to define truth, and then explore inductive reasoning. But first, we start with a discussion of the reading.
						</p>
					</introduction>
					
					
				
					<principle>
						<statement>
							<p>
								What is truth? What is fact? How are the two concepts related? How are they different? Under which category does the sentence <m>1+1=2</m> fall?
							</p>
	
						</statement>	
						
						<!-- <solution>
							<p>
								<em>Truth</em> refers to propositions which are correct and valid for all time, places, and people. It never changes. <em>Facts</em> refer to propositions supported by evidence. They are subject to change based on new evidence.
								There was some debate about the nature of truth relative to belief. 
								For instances, Christians believe that the historical person of Jesus is the Son of God. 
								Muslims do not. 
								Is this statement true for Christians but not for Muslims?
								Or is the proposition that the historical person of Jesus is the Son of God <em>true</em>, but Christians and Muslims have differing beliefs on its truth?
							</p>
	
						</solution> -->
	
	
					</principle>
	
					<activity xml:id="act-whats-my-world">
						<title>What's my world?</title>
						<statement>
							<p>
								In the game <em>What's my World?</em>, one person thinks of a single law that defines a hypothetical world (e.g., <q>My world does not contain things that start with the letter 'C'.</q>). The other players attempt to guess this governing law by taking turns asking questions of the creator, such as <q>Does your world contain dogs? Does it contain cats?</q> and so on. When one of the guessers believe they can identify the governing law, they ask the creator.
							</p>
							<p>
								Play a few rounds of this game, taking turns in the role of creator. <em>Other than asking the creator directly</em>, how could you be <em>certain</em> that you had determined the law of the world?
							</p>
						</statement>
						
						<solution>
							<p>
								We played various rounds of this game, but the only way we identified that we could know <em>for certain</em> that we had guessed the governing law correctly is by asking the creator. We can amass evidence and develop facts and a theory based on those facts, but we can only know for certain by asking the creator directly.
							</p>
	
						</solution>
	
	
					</activity>
					
					
					
					<definition>
						<p>
							<term>Inductive reasoning</term> is the process of drawing general conclusions from particular instances.
						</p>
					</definition>
					
					<p>
						The work of the guesser in <xref ref="act-whats-my-world" /> is to employ inductive reasoning to determine the general law put in place by the creator.
						This is the scientific process at its best: looking at the creation its orderliness and our creatureliness to infer larger governing principles.
						If you have taken a statistics course, this is the type of reasoning employed therein. If we have time in this unit, we may explore some examples of statistical reasoning.
					</p>
					<p>
						But how does this work in mathematics?
					</p>
	
	
	
					
					<exploration xml:id="expl-goldbach">
						<statement>
							<p>
								Consider the following equations.
							</p>
							<md>
								<mrow>6 \amp = 3 + 3</mrow>
								<mrow>8 \amp = 3 + 5</mrow>
								<mrow>10 \amp = 5 + 5</mrow>
								<mrow>12 \amp = 5 + 7</mrow>
								<mrow> \amp \vdots </mrow>
							</md>
							
							<ol>
								<li>The vertical ellipsis <m>\vdots</m> appearing below the four equations suggests that the equations form a pattern that continues. What do you think the next five equations are in this pattern?</li>
								<li>Your answer to the previous question may fit the data, but it may not be what we are ultimately looking for. Let's impose another rule: the number 9 is never allowed. Can you find a (possibly different) pattern that fits this new clue in addition to the existing data?</li>
								<li>What if we further restrict ourselves by outlawing the use of 15 and any even numbers? Can you find a pattern that fits these new clues in addition to the equations above? What are the next five equations in this case?</li>
							</ol>
	
	
						</statement>
						
						<solution>
							<p>
								A reasonable guess for the next five equations is:
							</p>
							<md>
								<mrow>14 \amp = 7+7</mrow>
								<mrow>16 \amp = 7+9</mrow>
								<mrow>18 \amp = 9+9</mrow>
								<mrow>20 \amp = 9+11</mrow>
								<mrow>22 \amp = 11+11</mrow>
							</md>
							<p>
								If we don't allow 9's, we could do:
							</p>
	
								<md>
								<mrow>14 \amp = 7+7</mrow>
								<mrow>16 \amp = 5+11</mrow>
								<mrow>18 \amp = 7+11</mrow>
								<mrow>20 \amp = 7+13</mrow>
								<mrow>22 \amp = 11+11</mrow>
							</md>
							<p>
								Since I didn't use 15, I don't have to change anything.
							</p>
							
							<p>
								The pattern described by the equations suggests a famous mathematical conjecture due to Goldbach: that every even whole number greater than or equal to 6 can be written as the sum of two (possibly equal) primes.
								Mathematicians have gathered a <em>lot</em> of evidence for this conjecture<fn>It's been verified for the first 4 quintillion even integers (which still isn't as many integers as there are configurations of the Cube!).</fn>, but until we have a conclusive <em>proof</em>, we won't know for sure if the pattern continues.
							</p>
	
							
	
	
	
						</solution>
	
						
	
					</exploration>
					
					<p>
						Let's look at one more activity.
					</p>
					
					<activity>
