				<section xml:id="Feb-12">
					<title>Feb. 12: The Resistance</title>
					
					
					
					
					<p>
						Today, we continue exploring logical/deductive reasoning. We'll first do it in the context of a game and related puzzles<fn>The puzzles are courtesy of <url href="https://www.taylor.edu/employees/faculty/derek-thompson">Derek Thompson</url> of Taylor University.</fn>.
						Given time, we'll start setting the stage for what became known as the <em>foundational crisis of mathematics</em>.
					</p>
					
					<subsection>
						<title>The Resistance</title>
						
						<p>
							To set the stage for a few puzzles, we'll play the social deduction game, <em><url href="https://boardgamegeek.com/boardgame/41114/resistance">The Resistance</url></em>.
							If you've ever played Werewolf or Mafia, this won't be too much of a stretch.
						</p>
						<p>
							The Resistance is set in a futuristic world where Rebels are trying to overthrow a sinister government, but Spies have invaded The Resistance.
							The Spies know who the other Spies are, but the Rebels don't know who anyone is.
							In the game, 5-10 players will pick teams to go on 5 <q>missions</q>.
							The Rebels win if three missions are successful.
							The Spies are trying to be put on the missions in order to sabotage them.
							If three missions are unsuccessful, the Spies win.
						</p>
						
						<subsubsection>
							<title>Setting up a mission</title>
							
							<p>
								At the beginning of the game, the Spies reveal themselves to each other, while the Rebels know no one's identity but their own.
								A leader is then nominated, who proposes a team to go on a mission (the teams vary in size from round to round).
								The group votes simultaneously and openly about whether to approve the proposed team for the mission.
								If the team is rejected, leadership is passed clockwise; otherwise, the team goes on the mission.
								If five teams are rejected in the same round, the Spies win <em>the entire game</em> automatically.
							</p>
						
						</subsubsection>
						
						<subsubsection>
							<title>Going on a mission</title>
							
							<p>
								There is nothing to <em>do</em> on a mission; each participant simply decides whether the mission <em>Succeeds</em> or <em>Fails</em> by playing the appropriate card.
								Rebels <em>must</em> play a Pass card; Spies may choose either card.
								If <em>any</em> card is a Fail card, the mission fails (unless playing with 7+, in which case two Fail cards are required).
								Players are free to say whatever they like, whether it is true or false.
								However, players may <em>not</em> reveal their identity card that indicates if they are a Spy or a Rebel.
							</p>
						
						</subsubsection>
						
						<subsubsection>
							<title>Playing the Game</title>
							
							<example>
								<statement>
									<p>
										Two people, Amanda and Bob, are elected to go on a mission.
										One Pass card is played, while one Fail card is played.
										
										If Amanda is a Rebel, what can we (validly) conclude about Bob? Is this sound?
									</p>
								</statement>
							</example>
							
							<p>
								Now, let's get into groups and play! Remember:
							</p>
							<ol>
								<li>Leader proposes a team for the mission.</li>
								<li> Everyone votes whether or not to accept the team for the mission.</li>
								<li>If the mission is not accepted, leadership rotates and the new leader proposes a team.</li>
								<li>If the mission is a go, those on the mission vote for it to succeed or fail.</li>
								<li>Rebels win if three missions succeed; Spies win if three fail or five consecutive teams are not accepted for the mission.</li>
								<li>Once you get the hang of the structure, try to think strategically and logically about the choices you're presented.</li>
							</ol>
							
							
						
						</subsubsection>
						
						<subsubsection>
							<title>Explorations</title>
							
							<exploration>
								<statement>
									<p>
										Suppose there are six players: Amanda, Bob, Carla, Derek, Ellie, and Fred (then there are two spies).
									</p>
									<p>
										Amanda and Bob go on the first mission; one Fail card and one Success card appear.
									</p>
									<p>
										Carla, Derek, and Fred go on the second mission; one Fail card and two Success cards appear.
									</p>
									<p>
										Who is definitely a Rebel?
									</p>
								</statement>
							</exploration>
							
							<exploration>
								<statement>
									<p>
										Again, suppose there are six players: Amanda, Bob, Carla, Derek, Ellie, and Fred (then there are two spies).
									</p>
									<p>
										Amanda and Derek go on the first mission; two Success cards appear.
									</p>
									<p>
										Carla, Fred, and Derek go on the second mission; one Fail card and two Success cards appear.
									</p>
									<p>
										Derek, Bob, Ellie, and Amanda go on the third mission; two Fail cards and two Success cards appear.
									</p>
									<p>
										Who is definitely a Spy?
									</p>
								</statement>
							</exploration>
							
							<exploration>
								<statement>
									<p>
										Suppose there are six players: Amanda, Bob, Carla, Derek, Ellie, and Fred (then there are two spies).
									</p>
									<p>
