				<exploration>
					<statement>
						<p>
							Determine the truth values of the following statements. Identify which row of <xref ref="table-implication" /> you are in.
						</p>
						<ol>
							<li>If <m>x</m> is negative, then <m>-5x</m> is positive.</li>
							<li>If we have Math 149 today, then it is Wednesday.</li>
							<li>If <m>9 > 5</m>, then dogs do not have wings.</li>
							<li>If <m>2=4</m>, then Calvin Coolidge is our greatest president.</li>
						</ol>
	
					</statement>
					<!-- 
	<solution>
						<p>As with conjunction and disjunction, there need be no causal relationship (or any relationship at all) between the constituents in an implication. To actually deduce the implication, however, usually does require a causal link to be established.</p>
						<ol>
							<li>This is true.</li>
						</ol>
	
					</solution>
	 -->
	
	
				</exploration>
	
	
				
				<p>
					The formalization of mathematical logic ramps up a bit when we consider conditional statements.
					It is important to remember that we define the truth value of the proposition <m>P \Rightarrow Q</m> <em>purely formally</em> based on the structure of the conditional statement and the truth values of the constituents <m>P</m> and <m>Q</m>.
					There need not be a causal relationship between <m>P</m> and <m>Q</m>!
				</p>
				
				<p>
					The last two rows of <xref ref="table-implication" /> are also worth a moment of our time.
					They state that if the statement <m>P</m><fn>Often called the <em>antecedent.</em></fn> is false, then the <em>implication</em> <m>P\Rightarrow Q</m> is <em>true</em>.
					Note that this is different than saying that <m>Q</m><fn>Often called the <em>consequent.</em></fn> is true.
					When the implication <m>P\Rightarrow Q</m> is true because <m>P</m> is false, we usually say that <m>P\Rightarrow Q</m> is <term>vacuously true</term>.
				</p>
				
				<activity>
					<statement>
						<p>
							Suppose Dr. Janssen promises that, if everyone has solved their Rubik's Cube by Friday, then he will bring Defenders (on pretzel with everything) to class<fn>This is purely hypothetical.</fn>.
							Unfortunately, a few students do not solve the Cube by Friday, so Dr. Janssen does not bring Defenders.
						</p>
	
						<p>
							Determine the truth value of the implication "If everyone can solve their Cubes by Friday, Dr. Janssen will bring Defenders to class".
							How does this help you think about vacuous truth?
						</p>
						
						
	
	
					</statement>
	
				</activity>
					
					<p>
						Last time, we learned about the push from mathematicians in the late 19th/early 20th century were trying to show that the axioms, the very foundations on which mathematics was built, were both <em>complete</em> (the truth of every sensible statement could be decided via deductions from the axioms) and <em>consistent</em> (one could never deduce contradictory statements from the axioms).
					</p>
					
					<p>
						For reasons which are hopefully clear, we'll assume that the axioms are consistent, that is, no contradictions will arise from them. (If contradictions <em>can</em> arise, we are in trouble indeed.)
						But if the axioms are consistent, can it be shown that they're complete?
						To answer this question, we dive into the realm of infinity.
					</p>
					
					<subsection>
						<title>Infinite Sets</title>
					
					
					<definition>
						<p>
							Let <m>S</m> and <m>T</m> be <term>sets</term>, which we may think of as collections of objects.
							We say that <m>S</m> and <m>T</m> have the same <term>cardinality</term> if there is a one-to-one correspondence between the objects of <m>S</m> and those of <m>T</m>, i.e., if each element of <m>S</m> can be paired up with one and only one unique element of <m>T</m>.
							In this case, we write <m>|S| = |T|</m>.
						</p>
					</definition>
					
					<activity>
						<statement>
							<p>
								Let <m>S = \{1,2,3,4\}</m>, <m>T=\{\square,\circ,\bigstar,\triangle\}</m>, and <m>U = \{\diamondsuit,\spadesuit,\clubsuit\}</m>.
							</p>
							<ol>
								<li>Can you find a one-to-one correspondence between <m>S</m> and <m>T</m>? Describe it, or explain why none exist.</li>
								<li>Can you find a one-to-one correspondence between <m>S</m> and <m>U</m>? Describe it, or explain why none exist.</li>
								<li>Can you find a one-to-one correspondence between <m>T</m> and <m>U</m>? Describe it, or explain why none exist.</li>
							</ol>
						</statement>
					</activity>
					
					<p>
						In order to explore infinity further, we need to set some notation.
					</p>
		
					<definition xml:id="def-number_sets">
						<p>
							We define the following sets of numbers.
						</p>
						<ol>
							<li>The <term>natural numbers</term> are given by <m>\mathbb{N} = \{1, 2, 3, \ldots\}</m>.</li>
							<li>The <term>whole numbers</term> are given by <m>\mathbb{W} = \{0,1,2,3,\ldots\}</m>.</li>
							<li>The <term>integers</term> are given by <m>\mathbb{Z} = \{\ldots, -3, -2, -1, 0, 1, 2, 3, \ldots\}</m>.</li>
							<li>The <term>even integers</term> are given by <m>2\mathbb{Z} = \{\ldots, -6, -4, -2, 0, 2, 4, 6, \ldots\}</m>.</li>
							<li>The set of <term>rational numbers</term> is denoted by <m>\mathbb{Q}</m> and consists of all fractions <m>\frac{a}{b}</m>, where <m>a,b</m> are integers and <m>b\ne 0</m>.</li>
							<li>The set of <term>real numbers</term> is denoted by <m>\mathbb{R}</m> and is given by all positive and negative infinite decimals (alternatively, every point on the number line).</li>
						</ol>
						</definition>
		
					<activity>
						<statement>
							<p>
								For the numbers that follow, identify all sets described in <xref ref="def-number_sets" /> they live in.
							</p>
							<ol>
								<li> <m>7</m></li>
								<li><m>-2</m></li>
								<li><m>\pi</m></li>
								<li><m>\frac{4}{3}</m></li>
								<li><m>0</m></li>
							</ol>
						</statement>
					</activity>
					
					<exploration>
						<title>Hilbert's Grand Hotel</title>
						<statement>
							<p>
								Hilbert's Grand Hotel is a full-service luxury hotel, having as many rooms as there are natural numbers. The room numbers are <m>1, 2, 3, 4, 5, \ldots</m>.  Suppose that every room is completely filled.
							</p>
							<ol>
								<li>A weary traveler arrives late in the night looking for a place to stay. Coud the manager find a way to give the traveler her own private room without having to ask anyone to leave the hotel?</li>
								<li>What if two travelers arrive? Three?</li>
								<li>What if infinitely many travelers arrive?</li>
								<li>What if Hilbert's Grand Hotel is empty and an infinite number of busses, each with an infinite number of passengers, arrived. Can room be found for all of them?</li>
							</ol>
						</statement>
					</exploration>
									
		
					
		
					<exploration xml:id="expl-countable">
						<statement>
							<p>
								For the following pairs of sets, determine whether a one-to-one correspondence between the two sets exists. If it does, describe it. If it does not, give a justification.
							</p>
							<ol>
								<li><m>\mathbb{N}</m> and <m>\mathbb{W}</m></li>
								<li><m>\mathbb{W}</m> and <m>\mathbb{Z}</m></li>
								<li><m>\mathbb{Z}</m> and <m>2\mathbb{Z}</m></li>
								<li><m>\mathbb{N}</m> and <m>2\mathbb{Z}</m></li>
								<li>(Challenge) <m>\mathbb{N}</m> and <m>\mathbb{Q}</m></li>
							</ol>
						</statement>
					</exploration>
					
					<exploration xml:id="expl-uncountable">
						<statement>
							<p>
								Let's explore the relationship between the cardinalities of <m>\mathbb{N}</m> and <m>\mathbb{R}</m> by considering the interval <m>[0,1]</m> consisting of all real numbers (points on the number line) <m>x</m> satisfying <m>0 \le x \le 1</m>.
								We will use the notation <m>0.a_1 a_2 a_3 \ldots</m> to denote the infinite decimal with tenths place value <m>a_1</m>, hundredths <m>a_2</m>, and so on.
							</p>
							<ol>
								<li>What is the relationship between <m>|\mathbb{R}|</m> and <m>|[0,1]|</m>?</li>
								<li>Suppose we have a one-to-one correspondence between <m>\mathbb{N}</m> and <m>[0,1]</m>. Explain why this means that we can write 
									<md>
										<mrow>1 \amp \leftrightarrow 0.d_{11}d_{12}d_{13}\ldots</mrow>
										<mrow>2 \amp \leftrightarrow 0.d_{21}d_{22}d_{23}\ldots</mrow>
										<mrow>3 \amp \leftrightarrow 0.d_{31}d_{32}d_{33}\ldots</mrow>
										<mrow> \amp \vdots </mrow>
									</md>
									where <m>d_{ij}</m> is the <m>j</m>th decimal digit of the <m>i</m>th number on the list.
									</li>
								<li>Define a real number <m>M = 0.e_1 e_2 e_3 \ldots</m> where <m>e_j = 2</m> if <m>d_{jj} \ge 5</m> and <m>e_j = 7</m> if <m>d_{jj} \lt 5</m>. Suppose the first three numbers on the list above are
									<md>
										<mrow> \amp 0.4548430426\ldots</mrow>
										<mrow> \amp 0.4007677961\ldots</mrow>
										<mrow> \amp 0.4702962689\ldots</mrow>
									</md>
									What is <m>M</m> in this case?
								</li>
								<li>In general, is it true that <m>0 \le M \le 1</m>?</li>
								<li>Where is <m>M</m> on the list in Question 2?</li>
								<li>What does your answer to the previous question suggest about the one-to-one correspondence we wrote down in Question 2?</li>
								<li>What does your answer to the previous question suggest about the relationship between <m>|\mathbb{N}|</m> and <m>|[0,1]|</m>? Between <m>|\mathbb{N}|</m> and <m>|\mathbb{R}|</m>?</li>
							</ol>
						</statement>
					</exploration>
		
					
					<principle xml:id="discussion-undecidable">
						<p>
							Given your responses to <xref ref="expl-countable" /> and <xref ref="expl-uncountable" />, do you think there is a set <m>S</m> such that <m>|S| \gt |\mathbb{N}|</m> and <m>|S| \lt |\mathbb{R}|</m>? Why or why not?
						</p>
					</principle>
					</subsection>
					
					<subsection>
						<title>The Incompleteness Theorems</title>
						
						<p>
							In 1931, the Austrian mathematical logician Kurt Godel resolved Hilbert's question in an unexpected way in his two <term>incompleteness theorems</term>.
						</p>
						
						<theorem>
							<title>Godel's First Incompleteness Theorem</title>
							<statement>
								<p>
									Any sufficiently strong consistent formal system contains undecidable statements.
								</p>
							</statement>
						</theorem>
						
						<p>
							That is, there are sensible statements that one can make which cannot be proved from within the system. In that case, we may adopt the undecidable statement or its negation as an additional axiom without causing any contradiction.
							The statement suggested by <xref ref="discussion-undecidable" /> is just such an undecidable statement.
						</p>
						
						<theorem>
							<title>Godel's Second Incompleteness Theorem</title>
							<statement>
								<p>
									The consistency of a consistent system cannot be established within the system.
								</p>
							</statement>
						</theorem>
						
						<p>
							We thus obtain limitations on the formal axiomatic approach to mathematics. Any consistent set of axioms and rules of inference strong enough to include arithmetic must contain undecidable statements. Furthermore, no sufficiently strong formal system can establish its own consistency!
						</p>
						
						
						<principle>
							<statement>
								<p>
									Godel's theorems leave mathematicians and students of mathematics in a precarious state. Consider the following questions for discussion.
								</p>
								<ol>
									<li>Godel's first theorem implies that that are mathematical  questions that do not have <q>one right answer</q>. What do you think of this when you consider the nature of mathematics and the ideas you've grown up with regarding what sort of discipline mathematics is?
									</li>
									<li>Godel's second theorem implies that the consistency of mathematics is taken as an article of faith. Yet our society seems to have an elevated role for quantitative arguments (e.g., how does one refute a statistic?). How can these theorems help us to think about the proper place of mathematics in society?</li>
								</ol>
							</statement>
						</principle>
						
						
					</subsection>
					
				</section>
				
				
				
				
