				<section xml:id="Feb-24">
					<title>Feb. 24: Reading Discussion II and Apportionment</title>
					
					
					<introduction>
						
						<p>
							Today we begin a short exploration of matheamtics and democracy. There are <em>lots</em> of different topics we could cover, but of special relevance to us this year is the notion of apportionment and the electoral college.
						</p>
						<p>
							Apportionment is the process by which the 435 seats in the U.S. House of Representatives are divided amongst the states. Every ten  years, following a census, Congress must pass a new apportionment bill. They will do so this year. A state's apportionment in Congress is also directly tied to its power in the electoral college, so the electoral vote after the 2024 presidential election will likely look different than it did following the 2020 election.
						</p>
						<p>
							The states then go through a redistricting process, modifying the geographic areas represented by their House members based on the new apportionment and their new understanding of their population's geographic distribution. There has been a lot of talk in the political (and mathematical) news about <em>gerrymandering</em>, the process of drawing district lines to favor one group over another. Given time, we'll explore this as well.
						</p>
						
					</introduction>
					
					<subsection>
						<title>Reading Discussion</title>
						
						<principle>
							<statement>
								<p>
									Discuss the reading with those sitting nearby. You may consider the following questions as a starting place, but feel free to follow the discussion wherever it leads.
								</p>
								<ul>
									<li>What mathematical laws, truths, or ideas do you rely on in your everyday life?</li>
									<li>Many things in the universe change over time. Do you find it surprising that the laws and theorems of mathematics do not change? Are there similar unchanging truths in other areas of inquiry?</li>
									<li>Has shallow knowledge of a topic or idea ever led you astray? How did you feel? How did you respond?</li>
									<li>What does knowing the <q>whole truth</q> of an idea/topic look like? To what degree is knowing the whole truth possible?</li>
									<li>How can matheamtical thinking equip you to converse with and respect people who hold different views than you on a subject?</li>
								</ul>
							</statement>
						</principle>
						
						
					</subsection>
					
					
